<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901221-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>901221-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Abreast of the Market:   Stocks Close Mixed After Dropping   On News of Shevardnadze's Move   ----   By Craig S. Smith   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2</SO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)STOCK INDEXES (NDX)U.S. STOCK MARKET STATISTICS (STT)NYSE GENERAL MARKET COMMENTARY (NYS)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- The stock market ended little changed, havingrecovered from an opening drop on news of Soviet ForeignMinister Eduard Shevardnadze's sudden resignation.   Mr. Shevardnadze quit amid growing domestic turmoil in theSoviet Union, warning that the country was slipping towarddictatorship.</LP><TEXT>   European markets tumbled on the news, and the stock markethere opened on a sharp downdraft. The Dow Jones IndustrialAverage plummeted 26 points before stabilizing and thenclimbing back to positive territory by noon.   The average ended with a 2.73-point gain at 2629.46.   &quot;They keep driving the market down but it snaps rightback,&quot; said Richard Eakle, president of Eakle Associates.   While the Shevardnadze news darkened the politicalbackdrop, traders say the market recovered as implacableportfolio managers continued their year-end buying.   &quot;A lot of people are doing a little dressing up today,&quot;said Edward J. Shopkorn, director of equity trading at MabonNugent. Mr. Shopkorn said the money managers were puttingexcess cash to work by buying highly liquid large-capitalizedstocks such as International Business Machines, which in turnhelped send the industrial average higher. IBM rose 1 to 1133/4.   The broader market remained fractionally lower, however.Standard andamp; Poor's 500-Stock Index eased 0.08 to 330.12 andthe New York Stock Exchange Composite Index slipped 0.03 to180.32.   Decliners led advancers, 813 to 726, with 507 stocksending unchanged. Volume totaled 174,700,000 shares, comparedwith 180.4 million Wednesday.   Dudley A. Eppel, senior vice president of equity tradingat Donaldson, Lufkin andamp; Jenrette, said trading volume shouldjump today as monthly futures contracts and options expire.Otherwise, said Mr. Eppel, the market should continue todrift as the end of the year approaches.   Aside from mounting war worries over the Middle East, Mr.Eakle of Eakle Associates said the stock market has somethings working in its favor that mitigate the downside riskin share prices.   &quot;Oil is still headed south, as are interest rates, andthere is a perception that inflation is receding,&quot; he said.   Crude oil for February delivery fell 54 cents yesterday to$26.39 a barrel.   Mr. Eakle also said that the internal dynamics of thestock market are showing signs of strength. Trading volume isincreasing on days that the market rises, he said, while thenumber of stocks that hit new lows each day is decreasing.   Some banking shares rallied again. The group has beenstrong since the Federal Reserve Board cut the discount rateto 6.5% from 7% on Tuesday.   Manufacturers Hanover jumped 1 5/8 to 24 1/8 on heavyvolume that included some dividend-related trading.Manufacturers said on Tuesday that it would pay its regular82-cent dividend to stock of record Jan. 2.   Citicorp gained 1/2 to 13 3/4, BankAmerica rose 1 3/8 to28, J.P. Morgan added 7/8 to 46, and Bankers Trust rose 5/8to 45 1/4.   First Chicago, whose First National Bank of Chicago unitcut its prime lending rate by 50 basis points to 9.5%, closedunchanged at 18 1/2.   Chase Manhattan was left behind, however. The stock fell3/8 to 10 3/4.   Travelers finished up 1/8 to 17 1/8 on volume of almosttwo million shares. Property/casualty insurer ContinentalCorp. has acquired at least 3% to 3.5% of Travelers' stock,according to USA Today. A 634,500-share block, representingabout 0.6% of Travelers' outstanding shares, changed handsshortly after noon.   Sprague Technologies added 3/8 to 3 7/8. The company saidit completed the sale of its semiconductor group to SankenElectric for $58 million in cash. Sprague said the sale willresult in a charge of about $49 million in the fourthquarter. Proceeds will be used to repay bank borrowings andfree up capital for further investment.   Symbol Technologies added 7/8 to 12 1/4. NCR decided towithdraw from the market a hand-held laser scanner thatSymbol claimed infringed on its patents. Symbol said itdismissed its pending patent-infringement suit against NCR.   Convex Computer rose 7/8 to 11 5/8. The company said itinstalled one of its supercomputers at the University ofHouston.   Urcarco fell 3/4 to 3 7/8. Merrill Lynch downgraded itsrating on the stock Wednesday and cut earnings estimates forthe company.   Rollins Environmental Services added 5/8 to 9 3/8. FirstBoston is recommending that its clients buy the stock.Rollins says maintenance at its Deer Park, Texas, incineratorhas been completed and the facility became operationalWednesday.   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. dropped 7/8 to 7 1/2. Anarticle in yesterday's New York Times highlighted thecompany's efforts to reschedule a mountain of short-termdebt. A number of small banks are refusing to go along,raising fears a settlement could be weeks, even months, away,the Times said.   L.A. Gear closed unchanged at 15. The company said lateWednesday that it completed a $360 million credit facilityarranged by Bank of America as agent for itself and asyndicate of domestic and international banks.   Hunt Manufacturing added 1 5/8 to 12 1/4. The companyboosted its quarterly dividend to eight cents a share from7.75 cents.   Coca-Cola Enterprises added 1/4 to 15 3/8. The companysaid its board approved a program to buy back as many as 15million common shares. The company said, however, that itdoesn't expect to buy back any shares under the program untilthe second or third quarter of 1991.   The American Stock Exchange Index fell 0.16 to 306.49.</TEXT></DOC>